svg.aria-label: DI Application Rate and the Unemployment Rate

text.style: fill: rgb(55, 11, 10); font-weight: bolder;

svg.text: 2010s​Over the last few years, the unemployment​rate and applications have fallen together.

text.style: fill: rgb(235, 63, 28); font-weight: bolder;

svg.text: Great Recession​During the Great Recession in the​late 2000s, both the unemployment​rate and share of DI applications​surged.

text.style: fill: rgb(235, 63, 28); font-weight: bolder;

svg.text: 2000s​Unemployment and applications​tracked each other during much​of the 2000s.

text.style: fill: rgb(6, 38, 53); font-weight: bolder;

svg.text: 1990s​Unemployment rose during the early 1990s​recession, taking applications with it, but​when unemployment fell, applications per​1,000 workers fell slightly.

text.style: fill: rgb(22, 150, 210); font-weight: bolder;

svg.text: 1980s​As the unemployment rate fell​in mid- and late-1980s, the​share of applications remained​unchanged, then fell in 1988​and 1989.
